{{Infobox building | name = [[Maria Zankovetska]] Theatre | native_name = Театр імені Марії Заньковецької | native_name_lang = Ukrainian | former_names = Teatr Skarbkowski (1842-1944) | alternate_names = Zankovetska Drama Theater | status = National [[Academic theater|Academic]] | image = Театр М.Заньковецької Львів.JPG | image_alt = | image_size = | caption = Facade of the theater, 2008 | map_type = | map_alt = | map_caption = | altitude = | building_type = | architectural_style = [[Neoclassical architecture]] | structural_system = | cost = | ren_cost = | client = | owner = [[Government of Ukraine]] | current_tenants = Theatrical troupe | landlord = [[Ministry of Culture (Ukraine)|Ministry of Culture]] | location = | address = vulytsia Lesi Ukrainky, 1 | location_town = Lviv | location_country = Ukraine | coordinates = {{coord|display=title|49.84395|N|24.027244|E|format=dms |type:landmark_region:UA}} | groundbreaking_date = 1832 | start_date = 1837 | completion_date = 1842 | opened_date = | inauguration_date = | renovation_date = | demolition_date = | destruction_date = | height = | architectural = | tip = | antenna_spire = | roof = | top_floor = | observatory = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = | floor_area = {{convert|95.45|x|76.25|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} | seating_type = Theater | seating_capacity = 1,460 | elevator_count = | architect = Jan Salzmann and Ludwig Pichl | architecture_firm = | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | other_designers = | quantity_surveyor = | main_contractor = | awards = | designations = | ren_architect = | ren_firm = | ren_str_engineer = | ren_serv_engineer = | ren_civ_engineer = | ren_oth_designers = | ren_qty_surveyor = | ren_awards = | parking = | url = [http://www.zankovetska.com.ua Official website] | embedded = | references = }}
'''[[Maria Zankovetska]] Theatre''' ({{lang-uk|Національний академічний український драматичний театр імені Марії Заньковецької}}, ''Natsionalnyi akademichnyi ukrayinskyi dramatychnyi teatr imeni Mariyi Zankovetskoyi''; {{lang-pl|Teatr Skarbkowski}}&nbsp;<ref name="archive"/>) is a drama theatre in the centre of [[Lviv]], Ukraine, at the intersection of Lesya Ukrayinka Street and Prospekt Svobody. The building was erected in the mid 19th century and until [[World War I]] was used as a theatre stage and a session hall of the regional council.
==History== [[File:Stanislav Skarbek Theatre in Lviv.jpg|thumb|left|Skarbek Theater, Lwów, water-colour by T. Rybrovsky, 1900]] The theatre was founded by Count [[:pl:Stanisław Skarbek|Stanisław Marcin Skarbek (pl)]] (1780–1848) [[Abdank coat of arms]], who as early as 1819 had applied for permission from the [[Austrian Empire|Austrian Imperial]] authorities to build it following the final [[Third Partition of Poland|Partition of Poland]].<ref name="teatry1">{{cite web|url=http://www.teatry.art.pl/!inne/teatralia3/teatrsk.htm |title=Teatralia3 - Teatr Skarbkowski |publisher=Teatry.art.pl |date= |accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref> Construction of the theatre’s [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] building began in 1837, the project was designed by architects Jan Salzmann and Ludwig Pichl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lwow.com.pl/semper/teatr.html |title=SEMPER FIDELIS - Okoliczności powstania i otwarcia Teatru Wielkiego we Lwowie |publisher=Lwow.com.pl |date= |accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref> The complex was built in the location of bastions, which surrounded the [[:uk:Низький замок|Lower Castle]] and its foundation was made of 16,000 oak logs. In 1842 it was the third biggest building of Central Europe.<ref name="archive">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090321024424/http://www.poznan.pl/mim/public/euro2012/pages.html?id=8127&ch=10854&p=10859&instance=1017&lang=pl&lhs=publications&rhs=publications&lhs=euro2012 Ukraina. UEFA Euro 2012: Lwów.] Internet Archive.</ref> Apart from the theatre itself, the complex also included apartments, for such famous personalities as [[Artur Grottger]] and [[Juliusz Kossak]]. On the opening day, March 28, 1842, a [[Franz Grillparzer]] play in the German language was presented, and on the next day, [[Aleksander Fredro]]'s play ''Śluby panieńskie'' was presented, this time in Polish.<ref name="teatry1"/>
In initial years, plays both in Polish and German were presented, and this lasted until 1871, when all German plays were withdrawn and the theatre became a Polish-language only. In 1872, operas were also presented, which made Skarbek Theatre the sole opera scene in [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galicia]].
In late years of the 19th century, the complex became insufficient, and in 1900, it was augmented by a brand new building of the [[The Lviv Theatre of Opera and Ballet|Grand Theatre]]. Skarbek Theatre was turned into a philharmonic, then into a cinema. Currently, it is home of the Ukrainian Dramatic Theatre of [[Maria Zankovetska]]. On May 18, 2008, celebrations of the 50th anniversary of the Polish People's Theatre of Lviv took place in the complex, with performance of a play by [[Marian Hemar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lwow.com.pl/teatr/skarbek/jubileusz.html |title=Jublileusz Polskiego Teatru we Lwowie |publisher=Lwow.com.pl |date=2008-08-31 |accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref>
